class Solution {
public:
    int maxTaskAssign(vector<int>& tasks, vector<int>& workers, int pills, int strength) {
        sort(tasks.begin(), tasks.end());
        sort(workers.begin(), workers.end());
        int n = tasks.size(), m = workers.size();
        int l = 0, r = min(n, m);
        while (l < r) {
            int mid = (l + r + 1) / 2;
            int p = pills;
            int j = m - mid;
            for (int i = n - mid; i < n; ++i) {
                if (tasks[i] > workers[j] + strength) {
                    --p;
                    if (workers[j] >= tasks[i]) {
                        ++j;
                    } else if (p < 0 || ++j == m) {
                        r = mid - 1;
                        break;
                    }
                } else {
                    ++j;
                }
            }
            if (l < r && j == m) {
                l = mid;
            }
        }
        return l;
    }
};
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n log n + m log m)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The main approach is to use binary search to find the maximum number of tasks that can be completed. We first sort the tasks and workers arrays. Then, we perform binary search on the range [0, min(n, m)] to find the maximum number of tasks that can be completed. For each mid value, we check if it's possible to complete mid tasks by iterating through the tasks array from the end and checking if the current task can be completed by the current worker with or without a pill. If we can't complete mid tasks, we decrease the right boundary; otherwise, we increase the left boundary. The key strength of this approach is its efficient use of binary search, which reduces the time complexity. 
